</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=naladini>naladini</A> at: 12/3/02 9:38:50 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=arkelon>Arkelon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#333333>(12/3/02 9:56:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8042.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Silly Mage lore question.</span><hr size=1> A magician's power comes from the ability to take raw magic power (mana) and convert it to true substance.<br>
<br>
The things we summon did not exist before we created them, and cease to exist in every way when the spell duration ends.  It is a conjuration, really.  Not a summoning.<br>
<br>
The use of a malachite (or other reagent) simply makes use of something referred to as complimentary magic.  The need to create larger magical items (i.e. elementals) would require too much mana by itself, but by using a reagent we reduce the mana cost to a reasonable level.  Magicians of sufficient skill no longer require the use of reagents as they have learned to focus their energy sufficiently to improve the efficiency of their casting (thus reducing the mana cost to the same amount used WITH a reagent).<br>
<br>
BTW, this all comes from several pieces of fiction (not from VI/EQ), where the subject of magic is explored in great detail.  The concept of complementary magic (along with several other types which escape me at the moment) combine to explain why certain types of magic produce permanent objects and others do not.  Why some kinds require somatic and verbal components and others do not.  The most powerful spells take the longest to cast, involve complicated somatic gestures and verbage, require a reagent and of course, mana.<br>
<br>
The base idea is that given only pure mana (and sufficient skill) it is possible to cast a spell.  It just requires a LOT of mana, making even simple things beyond the capability of most casters.  Each additional component reduces the mana cost sufficiently that most spells are now usable within a reasonable time.  Every EQ spell requires complicated somatic gestures and many require the use of reagents.  And of course, lengthy casting and reuse times.  Verbal components are not apparent in EQ.<br>
<br>
I developed a replacement magic system for D&amp;D with these ideas in mind, which produced an internally consistent spell system and allowed for an explanation of how magic items could be created, etc etc.  It was very complicaed, but well... magic IS complicated.  And only those people interested in creating their own spells or magic items needed to understand how it worked.<br>
<br>
